strings: !This program cannot be run in DOS mode.
Print numbers from FIRST (default 1) to LAST, moving by STEP (default 1).
-s, --separator STRING   use STRING for separating numbers (default: \n)
-w, --equal-width        equalize width by padding with leading zeroes
FIRST, INCREMENT, and LAST are interpreted as floating point values.
INCREMENT should be positive if FIRST is smaller than LAST, and negative
otherwise.  When given, the FORMAT argument must contain exactly one of
the printf-style, floating point output formats %%e, %%f, or %%g.
format string may not be specified when printing equal width strings
when the starting value is larger than the limit,
when the starting value is smaller than the limit,
